<div class="sect1">
<h2 id="academic_honesty"><a class="link" href="#academic_honesty">Academic Honesty</a></h2>
<div class="sectionbody">
<div class="paragraph">
<p>This course’s philosophy on academic honesty is best stated as "be reasonable." The course recognizes that interactions with classmates and others can facilitate mastery of the course’s material. However, there remains a line between enlisting the help of another and submitting the work of another. This policy characterizes both sides of that line.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>The essence of all work that you submit to this course must be your own. Collaboration on problem sets is not permitted except to the extent that you may ask classmates and others for help so long as that help does not reduce to another doing your work for you. Generally speaking, when asking for help, you may show your code to others, but you may not view theirs, so long as you and they respect this policy’s other constraints. Collaboration on the course’s final project is permitted to the extent prescribed by its specification.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Below are rules of thumb that (inexhaustively) characterize acts that the course considers reasonable and not reasonable. If in doubt as to whether some act is reasonable, do not commit it until you solicit and receive approval in writing from the course’s heads. Acts considered not reasonable by the course are handled harshly.</p>
</div>
<div class="sect2">
<h3 id="reasonable"><a class="link" href="#reasonable">Reasonable</a></h3>
<div class="ulist">
<ul>
<li>
<p>Communicating with classmates about problem sets' problems in English (or some other spoken language).</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Discussing the course’s material with others in order to understand it better.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Helping a classmate identify a bug in his or her code at Office Hours, elsewhere, or even online, as by viewing, compiling, or running his or her code, even on your own computer.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Incorporating snippets of code that you find online or elsewhere into your own code, provided that those snippets are not themselves solutions to assigned problems and that you cite the snippets' origins.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Reviewing past semesters' quizzes and solutions thereto.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Sending or showing code that you’ve written to someone, possibly a classmate, so that he or she might help you identify and fix a bug.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Sharing snippets of your own code online so that others might help you identify and fix a bug.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Turning to the web or elsewhere for instruction beyond the course’s own, for references, and for solutions to technical difficulties, but not for outright solutions to problem set’s problems or your own final project.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Whiteboarding solutions to problem sets with others using diagrams or pseudocode but not actual code.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Working with (and even paying) a tutor to help you with the course, provided the tutor does not do your work for you.</p>
</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
<div class="sect2">
<h3 id="not_reasonable"><a class="link" href="#not_reasonable">Not Reasonable</a></h3>
<div class="ulist">
<ul>
<li>
<p>Accessing a solution in CS50 Vault to some problem prior to (re-)submitting your own.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Asking a classmate to see his or her solution to a problem set’s problem before (re-)submitting your own.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Decompiling, deobfuscating, or disassembling the staff’s solutions to problem sets.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Failing to cite (as with comments) the origins of code or techniques that you discover outside of the course’s own lessons and integrate into your own work, even while respecting this policy’s other constraints.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Giving or showing to a classmate a solution to a problem set’s problem when it is he or she, and not you, who is struggling to solve it.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Looking at another individual’s work during a quiz.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Paying or offering to pay an individual for work that you may submit as (part of) your own.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Providing or making available solutions to problem sets to individuals who might take this course in the future.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Searching for, soliciting, or viewing a quiz’s questions or answers prior to taking the quiz.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Searching for or soliciting outright solutions to problem sets online or elsewhere.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Splitting a problem set’s workload with another individual and combining your work.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Submitting (after possibly modifying) the work of another individual beyond allowed snippets.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Submitting the same or similar work to this course that you have submitted or will submit to another.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Submitting work to this course that you intend to use outside of the course (e.g., for a job) without prior approval from the course’s heads.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Using resources during a quiz beyond those explicitly allowed in the quiz’s instructions.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Viewing another’s solution to a problem set’s problem and basing your own solution on it.</p>
</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>

<div class="sect1">
<h2 id="getting_started"><a class="link" href="#getting_started">Getting Started</a></h2>
<div class="sectionbody">
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Recall that the CS50 Appliance is a "virtual machine" (running an operating system called Ubuntu, which itself is a flavor of Linux) that you can run inside of a window on your own computer, whether you run Windows, Mac OS, or even Linux itself. To do so, all you need is a "hypervisor" (otherwise known as a "virtual machine monitor"), software that tricks the appliance into thinking that it’s running on "bare metal."</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Alternatively, you could buy a new computer, install Ubuntu on it (i.e., bare metal), and use that! But a hypervisor lets you do all that for free with whatever computer you already have. Plus, the CS50 Appliance is pre-configured for CS50, so, as soon as you install it, you can hit the ground running.</p>
</div>
<div class="sect2">
<h3 id="installing"><a class="link" href="#installing">Installing</a></h3>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>So let’s get a hypervisor and the CS50 Appliance installed on your computer. Head to <a href="https://manual.cs50.net/appliance/2014/#how_to_install_appliance">https://manual.cs50.net/appliance/2014/#how_to_install_appliance</a>, where instructions await. In particular, if running Mac OS, follow the instructions for VMware Fusion.  If running Windows or Linux, follow the instructions for VMware Workstation. <strong>Be sure to download version 2014 of the CS50 Appliance, not 19 or earlier.</strong></p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="sect2">
<h3 id="updating"><a class="link" href="#updating">Updating</a></h3>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Once you have the CS50 Appliance installed, go ahead and start it (per those same instructions). A small window should open, inside of which the appliance should boot. A few seconds or minutes later, you should find yourself logged in as John Harvard (whose username is <strong>jharvard</strong> and whose password is <strong>crimson</strong>), with John Harvard’s desktop before you.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p><strong>If you find that the appliance runs unbearably slow on your PC, particularly if several years old or a somewhat slow netbook, or if you see a hint about "long mode," try the instructions at <a href="https://manual.cs50.net/virtualization">https://manual.cs50.net/virtualization</a> and let us know if you still need a hand.</strong></p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Feel free to poke around, particularly the 50 Menu in the appliance’s bottom-left corner. You should find the graphical user interface (GUI), called Xfce, reminiscent of both Mac OS and Windows. Linux actually comes with a bunch of GUIs; Xfce is just one. If you’re already familiar with Linux, you’re welcome to install other software via <code>apt-get</code>, but the appliance should have everything you need for now. You’re also welcome to play with the appliance’s various features, per the instructions at <a href="https://manual.cs50.net/appliance/2014/#how_to_use_appliance">https://manual.cs50.net/appliance/2014/#how_to_use_appliance</a>, but this problem set will explicitly mention anything that you need know or do.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Even if you just downloaded the appliance, ensure that it’s completely up-to-date by opening a terminal window, as via <strong>Menu &gt; Accessories &gt; Terminal Emulator</strong>, typing</p>
</div>
<div class="listingblock">
<div class="content">
<pre class="CodeRay"><code class="bash language-bash">update50</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>and then hitting Enter on your keyboard. So long as your computer (and, thus, the appliance) has Internet access, the appliance should proceed to download and install any available updates.</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="sect2">
<h3 id="dropboxing"><a class="link" href="#dropboxing">Dropboxing</a></h3>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Next, follow the instructions at <a href="https://manual.cs50.net/appliance/2014/#how_to_enable_dropbox">https://manual.cs50.net/appliance/2014/#how_to_enable_dropbox</a> to configure the appliance to use Dropbox so that your work is automatically backed up, just in case something goes wrong with your appliance. (If you really don’t want to use Dropbox, that’s fine, but realize your files won’t be backed up as a result!) If you don’t yet have a Dropbox account, sign up when prompted for the free (2 GB) plan. You’re welcome to install Dropbox on your own computer as well (outside of the appliance), per <a href="https://www.dropbox.com/install">https://www.dropbox.com/install</a>, but no need if you’d rather not; just inside the appliance is fine.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>If you’re already a Dropbox user but don’t want your personal files to be synched into the appliance, simply enable <strong>Selective Sync</strong>, per the CS50 Manual’s instructions.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Incidentally, if curious how Dropbox itself works, allow us to introduce Thomas Carriero '08 and Alex Allain '06, both former CS50 TFs!</p>
</div>

<div class="sect2">
<h3 id="file_manager"><a class="link" href="#file_manager">File Manager</a></h3>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Okay, let’s create a folder (otherwise known as a "directory") in which your code for this problem set will soon live. Go ahead and double-click <strong>Home</strong> on John Harvard’s desktop (toward the appliance’s top-left corner). A window entitled <strong>jharvard - File Manager</strong> should appear, indicating that you’re inside of John Harvard’s "home directory" (i.e., personal folder). Then double-click the folder called <strong>Dropbox</strong>, at which point the window’s title should change to <strong>Dropbox - File Manager</strong>. Next select <strong>File &gt; Create Folder…</strong> in the window’s top-left corner, input a name of <strong>pset1</strong>, and then click <strong>Create</strong>. (If you misname the folder, control-click the misnamed folder, select <strong>Rename…</strong>, enter a new name, and click <strong>Rename</strong>.) Then double-click that <strong>pset1</strong> folder to open it. The window’s title should change to <strong>pset1 - File Manager</strong>, and you should see an otherwise empty folder (since you just created it).</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="sect2">
<h3 id="gedit"><a class="link" href="#gedit">gedit</a></h3>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Okay, go ahead and close any open windows, then select <strong>Menu &gt; Accessories &gt; gedit</strong>. (Recall that <strong>Menu</strong> is in the appliance’s bottom-left corner.) A window entitled <strong>Untitled Document 1 - gedit</strong> should appear, inside of which is a tab entitled <strong>Untitled Document 1</strong>. Clearly the document is just begging to be saved. Go ahead and type <code>hello</code> (or the ever-popular <code>asdf</code>) on line 1 of the document, and then notice how the tab’s name is now prefixed with an asterisk (<em>*</em>), indicating that you’ve made changes since the file was first opened. Select <strong>File &gt; Save</strong>, and a window entitled <strong>Save As</strong> should appear. Input <code>hello.txt</code> next to <strong>Name</strong>, then click <strong>Home</strong> under <strong>Places</strong>. You should then see the contents of John Harvard’s home directory. Double-click <strong>Dropbox</strong>, then double-click <strong>pset1</strong>, and you should find yourself inside that empty folder you created. Now, at the bottom of this same window, you should see that the file’s default <strong>Character Encoding</strong> is <strong>Unicode (UTF-8)</strong> and that the file’s default <strong>Line Ending</strong> is <strong>Unix/Linux</strong>. No need to change either; just notice they’re there. That the file’s <strong>Line Ending</strong> is <strong>Unix/Linux</strong> just means that <code>gedit</code> will insert (invisibly) <code>\n</code> at the end of any line of text that you type. Windows, by contrast, uses <code>\r\n</code>, and Mac OS uses <code>\r</code>, but more on those (delightfully annoying) details some other time.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Okay, click <strong>Save</strong> in the window’s bottom-right corner. The window should close, and you should see that the original window’s title is now <strong>hello.txt (~/Dropbox/pset1) - gedit</strong>. The parenthetical just means that <strong>hello.txt</strong> is inside of <strong>pset1</strong>, which is inside of <strong>Dropbox</strong>, which is inside of <strong>~</strong>, which is shorthand notation for John Harvard’s home directory. A useful reminder is all. The tab, meanwhile, should now be entitled <strong>hello.txt</strong> (with no asterisk, unless you accidentally hit the keyboard again).</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Okay, with <code>hello.txt</code> still open in <code>gedit</code>, notice that beneath your document is a "terminal window" (aka "terminal emulator"), a command-line (i.e., text-based) interface via which you can navigate the appliance’s hard drive and run programs (by typing their name). Notice that the window’s "prompt" is</p>
</div>
<div class="listingblock">
<div class="content">
<pre class="CodeRay"><code class="bash language-bash">jharvard@appliance (~):</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>which means that you are logged into the appliance as John Harvard and that you are currently inside of <strong>~</strong> (i.e., John Harvard’s home directory). If that’s the case, there should be a <strong>Dropbox</strong> directory somewhere inside. Let’s confirm as much.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Click somewhere inside of that terminal window, and the prompt should start to blink. Type</p>
</div>
<div class="listingblock">
<div class="content">
<pre class="CodeRay"><code class="bash language-bash">ls</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>and then Enter. That’s a lowercase L and a lowercase S, which is shorthand notation for "list." Indeed, you should then see a list of the folders inside of John Harvard’s home directory, among which is <strong>Dropbox</strong>! Let’s open that folder, followed immediately by the <strong>pset1</strong> folder therein. Type</p>
</div>
<div class="listingblock">
<div class="content">
<pre class="CodeRay"><code class="bash language-bash">cd Dropbox/pset1</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>or even</p>
</div>
<div class="listingblock">
<div class="content">
<pre class="CodeRay"><code class="bash language-bash">cd ~/Dropbox/pset1</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>followed by Enter to <span class="underline">c</span>hange your <span class="underline">d</span>irectory to <strong>~/Dropbox/pset1</strong> (ergo, <code>cd</code>). You should find that your prompt changes to</p>
</div>
<div class="listingblock">
<div class="content">
<pre class="CodeRay"><code class="bash language-bash">jharvard@appliance (~/Dropbox/pset1):</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>confirming that you are indeed now inside of <strong>~/Dropbox/pset1</strong> (i.e., a directory called <strong>pset1</strong> inside of a directory called <strong>Dropbox</strong> inside of John Harvard’s home directory). Now type</p>
</div>
<div class="listingblock">
<div class="content">
<pre class="CodeRay"><code class="bash language-bash">ls</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>followed by Enter. You should see <strong>hello.txt</strong>! Now, you can’t click or double-click on that file’s name there; it’s just text. But that listing does confirm that <strong>hello.txt</strong> is where we hoped it would be.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Let’s poke around a bit more. Go ahead and type</p>
</div>
<div class="listingblock">
<div class="content">
<pre class="CodeRay"><code class="bash language-bash">cd</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>and then Enter. If you don’t provide <code>cd</code> with a "command-line argument" (i.e., a directory’s name), it whisks you back to your home directory by default. Indeed, your prompt should now be:</p>
</div>
<div class="listingblock">
<div class="content">
<pre class="CodeRay"><code class="bash language-bash">jharvard@appliance (~):</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Phew, home sweet home. Make sense? If not, no worries; it soon will! It’s in this terminal window that you’ll soon be compiling your first program! For now, though, close <code>gedit</code> (via <strong>File &gt; Quit</strong>) and, with it, <strong>hello.txt</strong>.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Incidentally, if the need arises, know that you can transfer files to and from the appliance per the instructions at <a href="https://manual.cs50.net/appliance/2014/#how_transfer_files_between_appliance_and_your_computer">https://manual.cs50.net/appliance/2014/#how_transfer_files_between_appliance_and_your_computer</a>.</p>
</div>

<div class="sect1">
<h2 id="hello_c"><a class="link" href="#hello_c">Hello, C</a></h2>
<div class="sectionbody">
<div class="paragraph">
<p>First, a hello from Zamyla if you’d like a tour of what’s to come, particularly if less comfortable. Note that her version of the CS50 Appliance might look a bit different from yours, but not a problem.</p>
</div>
<div class="videoblock">
<div class="content">
<iframe width="960" height="540" src="//www.youtube.com/embed/HkQD6aw7oDc?rel=0" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen=""></iframe>
</div>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Shall we have you write your first program? Go ahead and launch <code>gedit</code>. (Remember how?) You should find yourself faced with another <strong>Unsaved Document 1</strong>. Go ahead and save the file as <code>hello.c</code> (not <code>hello.txt</code>) inside of <code>pset1</code>, just as before. (Remember how?) Once the file is saved, the window’s title should change to <strong>hello.c (~/Dropbox/pset1) - gedit</strong>, and the tab’s title should change to <strong>hello.c</strong>. (If either does not, best to close <code>gedit</code> and start fresh! Or ask for help!)</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Go ahead and write your first program by typing these lines into the file (though you’re welcome to change the words between quotes to whatever you’d like):</p>
</div>
<div class="listingblock">
<div class="content">
<pre class="CodeRay"><code class="c language-c"><span class="preprocessor">#include</span> <span class="include">&lt;stdio.h&gt;</span>

<span class="predefined-type">int</span> main(<span class="directive">void</span>)
{
    printf(<span class="string"><span class="delimiter">"</span><span class="content">hello, world</span><span class="char">\n</span><span class="delimiter">"</span></span>);
}</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Notice how <code>gedit</code> adds "syntax highlighting" (i.e., color) as you type. Those colors aren’t actually saved inside of the file itself; they’re just added by <code>gedit</code> to make certain syntax stand out. Had you not saved the file as <code>hello.c</code> from the start, <code>gedit</code> wouldn’t know (per the filename’s extension) that you’re writing C code, in which case those colors would be absent.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Do be sure that you type in this program just right, else you’re about to experience your first bug! In particular, capitalization matters, so don’t accidentally capitalize words (unless they’re between those two quotes). And don’t overlook that one semicolon. C is quite nitpicky!</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>When done typing, select <strong>File &gt; Save</strong> (or hit ctrl-s), but don’t quit. Recall that the leading asterisk in the tab’s name should then disappear. Click anywhere in the terminal window beneath your code, and its prompt should start blinking. But odds are the prompt itself is just</p>
</div>
<div class="listingblock">
<div class="content">
<pre class="CodeRay"><code class="bash language-bash">jharvard@appliance (~):</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>which means that, so far as the terminal window’s concerned, you’re still inside of John Harvard’s home directory, even though you saved the program you just wrote inside of <code>~/Dropbox/pset1</code> (per the top of <code>gedit</code>'s window). No problem, go ahead and type</p>
</div>
<div class="listingblock">
<div class="content">
<pre class="CodeRay"><code class="bash language-bash">cd Dropbox/pset1</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>or</p>
</div>
<div class="listingblock">
<div class="content">
<pre class="CodeRay"><code class="bash language-bash">cd ~/Dropbox/pset1</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>at the prompt, and the prompt should change to</p>
</div>
<div class="listingblock">
<div class="content">
<pre class="CodeRay"><code class="bash language-bash">jharvard@appliance (~/Dropbox/pset1):</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>in which case you’re where you should be! Let’s confirm that <code>hello.c</code> is there. Type</p>
</div>
<div class="listingblock">
<div class="content">
<pre class="CodeRay"><code class="bash language-bash">ls</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>at the prompt followed by Enter, and you should see both <code>hello.c</code> and <code>hello.txt</code>? If not, no worries; you probably just missed a small step. Best to restart these past several steps or ask for help!</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Assuming you indeed see <code>hello.c</code>, let’s try to compile! Cross your fingers and then type</p>
</div>
<div class="listingblock">
<div class="content">
<pre class="CodeRay"><code class="bash language-bash">make hello</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>at the prompt, followed by Enter. (Well, maybe don’t cross your fingers whilst typing.) To be clear, type only <code>hello</code> here, not <code>hello.c</code>. If all that you see is another, identical prompt, that means it worked! Your source code has been translated to object code (0s and 1s) that you can now execute. Type</p>
</div>
<div class="listingblock">
<div class="content">
<pre class="CodeRay"><code class="bash language-bash">./hello</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>at your prompt, followed by Enter, and you should see whatever message you wrote between quotes in your code! Indeed, if you type</p>
</div>
<div class="listingblock">
<div class="content">
<pre class="CodeRay"><code class="bash language-bash">ls</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>followed by Enter, you should see a new file, <code>hello</code>, alongside <code>hello.c</code> and <code>hello.txt</code>.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>If, though, upon running <code>make</code>, you instead see some error(s), it’s time to debug! (If the terminal window’s too small to see everything, click and drag its top border upward to increase its height.) If you see an error like expected declaration or something no less mysterious, odds are you made a syntax error (i.e., typo) by omitting some character or adding something in the wrong place. Scour your code for any differences vis-à-vis the template above. It’s easy to miss the slightest of things when learning to program, so do compare your code against ours character by character; odds are the mistake(s) will jump out! Anytime you make changes to your own code, just remember to re-save via <strong>File &gt; Save</strong> (or ctrl-s), then re-click inside of the terminal window, and then re-type</p>
</div>

</div>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>at your prompt, followed by Enter. (Just be sure that you are inside of <code>~/Dropbox/pset1</code> within your terminal window, as your prompt will confirm or deny.) If you see no more errors, try running your program by typing</p>

<h2 id="cs50_check"><a class="link" href="#cs50_check">CS50 Check</a></h2>
<div class="sectionbody">
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Now let’s see if the program you just wrote is correct! Included in the CS50 Appliance is <code>check50</code>, a command-line program with which you can check the correctness of (some of) your programs.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>If not already there, navigate your way to <code>~/Dropbox/pset1</code> by executing the command below.</p>
</div>
<div class="listingblock">
<div class="content">
<pre class="CodeRay"><code class="bash language-bash">cd ~/Dropbox/pset1</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>If you then execute</p>
</div>
<div class="listingblock">
<div class="content">
<pre class="CodeRay"><code class="bash language-bash">ls</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>you should see, at least, <code>hello.c</code>. Be sure it’s indeed spelled <code>hello.c</code> and not <code>Hello.c</code>, <code>hello.C</code>, or the like. If it’s not, know that you can rename a file by executing</p>
</div>
<div class="listingblock">
<div class="content">
<pre class="CodeRay"><code class="bash language-bash">mv source destination</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>where <code>source</code> is the file’s current name, and <code>destination</code> is the file’s new name. For instance, if you accidentally named your program <code>Hello.c</code>, you could fix it as follows.</p>
</div>
<div class="listingblock">
<div class="content">
<pre class="CodeRay"><code class="bash language-bash">mv Hello.c hello.c</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Okay, assuming your file’s name is definitely spelled <code>hello.c</code> now, go ahead and execute the below. Note that <code>2014.fall.pset1.hello</code> is just a unique identifier for this problem’s checks.</p>

<pre class="CodeRay"><code class="bash language-bash">check50 2014.fall.pset1.hello hello.c</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Assuming your program is correct, you should then see output like</p>
</div>
<div class="listingblock">
<div class="content">
<pre class="CodeRay"><code><span class="green">:) hello.c exists</span>
<span class="green">:) hello.c compiles</span>
<span class="green">:) prints "hello, world\n"</span></code></pre>
</div>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>where each green smiley means your program passed a check (i.e., test). You may also see a URL at the bottom of <code>check50</code>'s output, but that’s just for staff (though you’re welcome to visit it).</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>If you instead see yellow or red smileys, it means your code isn’t correct! For instance, suppose you instead see the below.</p>
</div>
<div class="listingblock">
<div class="content">
<pre class="CodeRay"><code><span class="red">:( hello.c exists</span>
  \ expected hello.c to exist
<span class="yellow">:| hello.c compiles</span>
  \ can't check until a frown turns upside down
<span class="yellow">:| prints "hello, world\n"</span>
  \ can't check until a frown turns upside down</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Because <code>check50</code> doesn’t think <code>hello.c</code> exists, as per the red smiley, odds are you uploaded the wrong file or misnamed your file. The other smileys, meanwhile, are yellow because those checks are dependent on <code>hello.c</code> existing, and so they weren’t even run.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Suppose instead you see the below.</p>
</div>
<div class="listingblock">
<div class="content">
<pre class="CodeRay"><code><span class="green">:) hello.c exists</span>
<span class="green">:) hello.c compiles</span>
<span class="red">:( prints "hello, world\n"</span>
  \ expected output, but not "hello, world"</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Odds are, in this case, you printed something other than <code>hello, world\n</code> verbatim, per the spec’s expectations. In particular, the above suggests you printed <code>hello, world</code>, without a trailing newline (<code>\n</code>).</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Know that <code>check50</code> won’t actually record your scores in CS50’s gradebook. Rather, it lets you check your work’s correctness <em>before</em> you submit your work. Once you actually submit your work (per the directions at this spec’s end), CS50’s staff will use <code>check50</code> to evaluate your work’s correctness officially.</p>

<div class="sect1">
<h2 id="time_for_change"><a class="link" href="#time_for_change">Time for Change</a></h2>
<div class="sectionbody">
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Speaking of money, "counting out change is a blast (even though it boosts mathematical skills) with this spring-loaded changer that you wear on your belt to dispense quarters, dimes, nickels, and pennies into your hand." Or so says <a href="http://hearthsong.com/">the website</a> on which we found this here accessory (for ages 5 and up).</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p><span class="image"><img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="Change-Making Accessory"></span></p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Of course, the novelty of this thing quickly wears off, especially when someone pays for a newspaper with a big bill. Fortunately, computer science has given cashiers everywhere ways to minimize numbers of coins due: greedy algorithms.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>According to the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST), a <a href="http://www.nist.gov/dads/HTML/greedyalgo.html">greedy algorithm</a> is one "that always takes the best immediate, or local, solution while finding an answer. Greedy algorithms find the overall, or globally, optimal solution for some optimization problems, but may find less-than-optimal solutions for some instances of other problems."</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>What’s all that mean? Well, suppose that a cashier owes a customer some change and on that cashier’s belt are levers that dispense quarters, dimes, nickels, and pennies. Solving this "problem" requires one or more presses of one or more levers. Think of a "greedy" cashier as one who wants to take, with each press, the biggest bite out of this problem as possible. For instance, if some customer is owed 41¢, the biggest first (i.e., best immediate, or local) bite that can be taken is 25¢. (That bite is "best" inasmuch as it gets us closer to 0¢ faster than any other coin would.) Note that a bite of this size would whittle what was a 41¢ problem down to a 16¢ problem, since 41 - 25 = 16. That is, the remainder is a similar but smaller problem. Needless to say, another 25¢ bite would be too big (assuming the cashier prefers not to lose money), and so our greedy cashier would move on to a bite of size 10¢, leaving him or her with a 6¢ problem. At that point, greed calls for one 5¢ bite followed by one 1¢ bite, at which point the problem is solved. The customer receives one quarter, one dime, one nickel, and one penny: four coins in total.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>It turns out that this greedy approach (i.e., algorithm) is not only locally optimal but also globally so for America’s currency (and also the European Union’s). That is, so long as a cashier has enough of each coin, this largest-to-smallest approach will yield the fewest coins possible.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>How few? Well, you tell us. Write, in a file called <code>greedy.c</code> in your <code>~/Dropbox/pset1</code> directory, a program that first asks the user how much change is owed and then spits out the minimum number of coins with which said change can be made. Use <code>GetFloat</code> from the CS50 Library to get the user’s input and <code>printf</code> from the Standard I/O library to output your answer. Assume that the only coins available are quarters (25¢), dimes (10¢), nickels (5¢), and pennies (1¢).</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>We ask that you use <code>GetFloat</code> so that you can handle dollars and cents, albeit sans dollar sign. In other words, if some customer is owed $9.75 (as in the case where a newspaper costs 25¢ but the customer pays with a $10 bill), assume that your program’s input will be <code>9.75</code> and not <code>$9.75</code> or <code>975</code>. However, if some customer is owed $9 exactly, assume that your program’s input will be <code>9.00</code> or just <code>9</code> but, again, not <code>$9</code> or <code>900</code>. Of course, by nature of floating-point values, your program will likely work with inputs like <code>9.0</code> and <code>9.000</code> as well; you need not worry about checking whether the user’s input is "formatted" like money should be. And you need not try to check whether a user’s input is too large to fit in a <code>float</code>. But you should check that the user’s input makes cents! Er, sense. Using <code>GetFloat</code> alone will ensure that the user’s input is indeed a floating-point (or integral) value but not that it is non-negative. If the user fails to provide a non-negative value, your program should re-prompt the user for a valid amount again and again until the user complies.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Incidentally, do beware the inherent imprecision of floating-point values. For instance, <code>0.01</code> cannot be represented exactly as a float. Try printing its value to, say, <code>50</code> decimal places, with code like the below:</p>
</div>
<div class="listingblock">
<div class="content">
<pre class="CodeRay"><code class="c language-c"><span class="predefined-type">float</span> f = <span class="float">0</span><span class="float">.01</span>;
printf(<span class="string"><span class="delimiter">"</span><span class="content">%.50f</span><span class="char">\n</span><span class="delimiter">"</span></span>, f);</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Before doing any math, then, you’ll probably want to convert the user’s input entirely to cents (i.e., from a <code>float</code> to an <code>int</code>) to avoid tiny errors that might otherwise add up! Of course, don’t just cast the user’s input from a <code>float</code> to an <code>int</code>! After all, how many cents does one dollar equal? And be careful to <a href="https://cs50.harvard.edu/resources/cppreference.com/stdmath/round.html">round</a> and not truncate your pennies!</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Not sure where to begin? Not to worry, start with a walkthrough:</p>
</div>
<div class="videoblock">
<div class="content">
<iframe width="960" height="540" src="//www.youtube.com/embed/9dZzyl7dCuw?rel=0" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen=""></iframe>
</div>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Incidentally, so that we can automate some tests of your code, we ask that your program’s last line of output be only the minimum number of coins possible: an integer followed by <code>\n</code>. Consider the below representative of how your own program should behave, wherein underlined text is some user’s input.</p>
</div>
<div class="listingblock">
<div class="content">
<pre class="CodeRay"><code>jharvard@appliance (~/Dropbox/pset1): <span class="underline">./greedy</span>
O hai! How much change is owed?
<span class="underline">0.41</span>
4</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>By nature of floating-point values, that user could also have inputted just <code>.41</code>. (Were they to input <code>41</code>, though, they’d get many more coins!)</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Of course, more difficult users might experience something more like the below.</p>
</div>
<div class="listingblock">
<div class="content">
<pre class="CodeRay"><code>jharvard@appliance (~/Dropbox/pset1): <span class="underline">./greedy</span>
O hai! How much change is owed?
<span class="underline">-0.41</span>
How much change is owed?
<span class="underline">-0.41</span>
How much change is owed?
<span class="underline">foo</span>
Retry: <span class="underline">0.41</span>
4</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Per these requirements (and the sample above), your code will likely have some sort of loop. If, while testing your program, you find yourself looping forever, know that you can kill your program (i.e., short-circuit its execution) by hitting ctrl-c (sometimes a lot).</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>We leave it to you to determine how to compile and run this particular program!</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>If you’d like to check the correctness of your program with <code>check50</code>, you may execute the below.</p>
</div>
<div class="listingblock">
<div class="content">
<pre class="CodeRay"><code class="bash language-bash">check50 2014.fall.pset1.greedy greedy.c</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>And if you’d like to play with the staff’s own implementation of <code>greedy</code> in the appliance, you may execute the below.</p>
</div>
<div class="listingblock">
<div class="content">
<pre class="CodeRay"><code class="bash language-bash">~cs50/pset1/greedy</code></pre>
</div>

If you move your mouse toward the window’s lefthand side, you should see a list of the files you uploaded.  Click each to confirm the contents of each.  (No need to click any other buttons or icons.)  If confident that you submitted the files you intended, consider your source code submitted!  If you’d like to re-submit different (or modified) files, simply return to <a href="http://cs50.edx.org/submit">cs50.edx.org/submit</a> and repeat these steps.  You may re-submit as many times as you’d like; we’ll grade your most recent submission, so long as it’s before the deadline.</p>
